text.html: While the property market wallows in its bubble or crisis or whatever and people under 30 are repeatedly told they’ll be lucky to fully own a kettle 10 years from now, there are actually pockets of the capital that are still affordable to live in. What?! Yeah, and Streatham (or St. Reatham’s if you like making things sound fancy) is one of those ends. Guess we should probably have it large then, eh?

Best for… finding a cool spot where all seemed lost

tip.text:
It's only small, but Cut the Mustard is a cafe with a big heart. Brunches here offer all the usual suspects, nicely made, and served with a good bit of chat from the staff. They also get in other baked good stuff too, like black pudding sausage rolls (hell yes), plus there's a small dinner menu on Fridays and Saturdays that's worth a look if you're nearby.

The deli here gets in beers from microbreweries like Clarence & Fredericks down in Croydon. Their juices are also popular in the area for those getting all healthy and that.

text.text: This might seem like the middle of nowhere, but every middle of nowhere can do with a reason for checking it out. Enter Cut the Mustard, bringing the good people of somewhere-between-Streatham-and-Mitcham a local hangout to shout about. Jimmy bravely left his cushty cheffing job to start this passion project: top quality food, local produce, regulars he knows on first-name terms. The locals love it and people are starting to flock from further afield. And now they're even doing dinner too.
Best for… starting your day with a splash

tip.text:
Unless there's a heatwave, this one is probably best left to serious swimmers. Open since 1906, it's the largest swimming pool in the UK at a staggering 90 metres long - and you know what your mother told you about starting something you won't be able to finish. Notorious for its invigorating water and colourful changing room, this is only open to the public in the summer; winter swims require membership.

Opening times are subject to seasons so please check the website for details.

text.html: Everyone loves to splash about in the open air every now and then, and while SW16 might not quite be Venice Beach, the Tooting Bec Lido is a cracking spot for some al fresco front-crawling. It’s freshwater too, so you can pretend you’re in a river or whatever: remember that there’s no chlorine to protect you from some kid’s wee though. Officially open to the public between May and September, we went in April and the stylus was open and people were swimming so…

Best for… kicking back with a cawfee

tip.text:
This is a lovely spot for wiling away a rainy day or getting involved in a spot of remote working. Boyce da Roca's charm lies in its rustic simplicity: a genuinely chilled environment; quality food; great music. All the veg here comes from Covent Garden Market, while pork is sourced from a small farm in Kent.

Quiches, salads and delightful breakfasts on sourdough are on the cards here: get your avo smashed or have a bang on a cracking eggs benedict - either way you shan't be disappointed. If you're looking to purge your body of toxins then grab a chia smoothie: chia seeds, coconut milk, banana, honey & oats. Yum.

text.text: If you’re into chilling the fuck out, listening to relaxing music and tucking into healthy and homely breakfast-y food then thank us now. Mark Boyce is a lovely Kiwi chap looking to avoid the uppity, hoity-toity contemporary cafe culture - first and foremost, it’s gotta be somewhere you wanna spend time in. Chuck in some delightful stuff on toast, good coffee, smoothies and fresh juices and Bob’s your uncle.

tip.text: Bravi Ragazzi ('Good Fellas' in Italian) are all about their roots, which is why they’re absolutely killing the Neapolitan pizza game right now. Listen, you can even get a Margarita (unadventurous, admittedly) for £6.50. Don’t be fooled by the basic interior, this woodfire oven is birthing some of South LDN’s finest circular treats - and the guys doing it are as warm and friendly as anything: bravi ragazzi indeed.

Best for… coffee by day, wine by night

tip.text: Half way down the high street, tucked behind its grey visage, sits Brooks & Gao. The unassuming set up speaks volumes about the owner's confidence in their mediterranean menu to speak for itself. A stalwart on the agenda for all the yummy mummies and trendy youngsters in Streatham alike - expect to find spiced pinto beans on toast, a seasonal salad, or a delicious freshly made sandwich in this incredible cafe. A perfect alternative to your regular brunch offering, with no avocado in sight, brave!

text.html: More Italians, more cause for excitement. The concept of moonlighting has always carried an air of intrigue, so it’s definitely cool if your local daytime coffee spot masquerades as a wine bar, offering cheese boards and charcuterie plates in the evenings. Brooks & Gao does precisely this: other cafes, take note.

tip.text:
What's a neighbourhood without a local boozer? Not a neighbourhood, that's what. The Earl Ferrers is holding it down for the people of Streatham: real ales, a weekly music quiz, comfy sofas and a short (but sweet) food menu. Skint for date-night? Don't fret, for £20 you can get yourself a meal for two and a bottle of house wine.

The antique mirror, bookshelf and large STREATHAM sign only add to the cosy feeling of locality and homeliness. Guess what - they've even got Red Stripe on tap, which is surprisingly rare these days.

text.html: This cosy local pub has a lovely surprise up its sleeve for Streatham’s sweethearts - you’ll find it on the menu, under the Cheap Date Night heading. Wagwan? Grilled lamb chops, baba ghanoush, tabbouleh salad, smoked harissa, garlic bread and a bottle of house white. All for 20 bob. Don’t act like that’s not impressive. There’s a new meal deal in town, move over Sainsbury’s.

Best for… live Latin music and Mediterranean munch

tip.text:
This lovely spot brings a slice of sunny Spain to Streatham. Owned by two musicians (Spanish and Portuguese respectively), there's no little amount of vibrancy and passion about this hangout: live music nights throughout the month, from Flamenco to Cuban, complete with the likes of mojitos and caipirinhas.

We go fucking nuts for natas (those dreamy, creamy, delicious custard tarts native to Portugal), like in a really big way. Claudia (Portuguese co-owner) whips up homemade ones here everyday, so bet your squeaky arse that these are the real deal. Have your fill of eggs, chorizo, pastries and coffee at this friendly, local cafe.

Best for... a stylish neighbourhood eaterie

tip.text:
This charming neighbourhood haunt in Streatham is just the kind of place you want in your hood. It serves tasty food, decent coffee, and some nice wines and beers; plus it’s bright and airy and generally a nice place to be. The definition of a neighbourhood gem.

Come for brunch and you’ll find all the usual suspects: poachies, English muffins and pancakes alongside some more lunchy options. You can also go bottomless on the booze if you’re looking to get loose. At dinner time it’s a tantalising menu of things like roast Cornish hake, Wiltshire venison and some sexy puds. It’s fancy British dining with a (just about) reasonable price tag.

text.text: This friendly neighbourhood eatery has a certain style about it, and we admire a place with a bit of gumption. It does a little bit of brunch, lunch and dinner, serving up modern British cuisine without the hefty price tag you'd associate with fine dining. Okay, we're still looking at around £20 a meal, but if you want to go out for a semi-fancy thing this is a safe bet. Start with the blackened mackerel and end with their baked chocolate pudding.
